{{Nihongo|'''Hideshi Ishikawa'''|石川 日出志|Ishikawa Hideshi|born 1954}} is a Japanese archaeologist. Since 1978 he has been on the faculty of [[Meiji University]], in the Archaeology Department. He is considered an expert in the [[Yayoi]] period and the Bronze-Iron Age history and culture of the Korean peninsula,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.meiji.ac.jp/bungaku/teachingstaff/teacher_a/ishikawahide.html|title=石川日出志|publisher=Meiji University|accessdate=11 May 2015|language=Japanese}}</ref> and [[Jōmon period|Jōmon]] culture and pottery.<ref name="Habu2004">{{cite book|last=Habu|first=Junko|title=Ancient Jomon of Japan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vGnAbTyTynsC&pg=PA274|date=29 July 2004|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-77670-7|page=274}}</ref><ref name="呉清恵2011">{{cite book|author=呉清恵|title=Cosmogonical Worldview of Jomon Pottery|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hxulspIN_2UC&pg=PA213|date=November 2011|publisher=株式会社　三恵社|isbn=978-4-88361-924-5|page=213}}</ref> He has published several books and papers, including books about ruins of the Yayoi era (2008) and on agrarian society in ancient Japanese history (2010).

